{"id":8932,"date":"2019-02-04T00:27:49","date_gmt":"2019-02-04T00:27:49","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/?p=8932"},"modified":"2019-07-06T13:27:18","modified_gmt":"2019-07-06T13:27:18","slug":"introduction-to-azure-devops","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/02\/04\/introduction-to-azure-devops\/","title":{"rendered":"Introduction to Azure DevOps"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"#_Toc500069570\">Introduction<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069571\">How to access to your organizations and projects<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069572\">Kanban boards and backlogs<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069573\">Azure repos, Files, Commits, Pushes and Tags<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069574\">Azure pipelines<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069575\">Azure test plans and Artifacts<\/a><br \/>\n<a href=\"#_Toc500069576\">Conclusion<\/a><\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069570\"><\/a>Introduction<\/h2>\n<p>In this post I am going to introduce you to Azure DevOps, set of cloud hosted DevOps services that work for any language, targeting any platform. With Azure DevOps you can turn an idea into working piece of software. You can plan your project with agile tools, manage your test plans from the web, version your code using Git and deploy your solutions to incredible cross-platform CI\/CD system, and you can do all of this while getting full traceability and visibility across your development activities.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"blue\"><span class=\"ion-tip\">Tip (<strong><a href=\" https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/06\/08\/getting-started-with-kubernetes-cluster-ci-cd-for-azure-kubernetes-service\/ \"> Kubernetes cluster for beginner <\/a>)<\/strong><\/span> For more information about how to work with Kubernetes cluster and deploy it to <strong>Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) <\/strong>and work with <strong>Azure Container Registry<\/strong>, see <strong><a href=\" https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/06\/08\/getting-started-with-kubernetes-cluster-ci-cd-for-azure-kubernetes-service\/ \">Kubernetes cluster for beginner<\/a><\/strong><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069571\"><\/a> How to access to your organizations and projects<\/h2>\n<p>Go to dev.azure.com and your Azure DevOps page with Demonstrations will be opened. From Demonstrations page, you can see your Projects, your Work Items and your Pull Requests. On the Projects page, as you hover over the tiles (image 1), you can see which services each project uses. You can use as much or as little of Azure DevOps as you need.<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8933\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8933\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8933\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-1-Projects-page.png\" alt=\"Image 1 - Projects page\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-1-Projects-page.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-1-Projects-page-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-1-Projects-page-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-1-Projects-page-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8933\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 1 &#8211; Projects page<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>On the My Work Items page, you can see all work that is assigned to you and on the My Pull Request page you can see listed all pull requests that needs your attention. Clicking on Projects tile takes you to the Summary page, where you can quickly see the description about the project, project stats and team members (image 2).<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8934\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8934\" style=\"width: 1366px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8934\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-2-Summary-page.png\" alt=\"Image 2 - Summary page\" width=\"1366\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-2-Summary-page.png 1366w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-2-Summary-page-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-2-Summary-page-768x432.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-2-Summary-page-1024x576.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1366px) 100vw, 1366px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8934\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 2 &#8211; Summary page<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>From the left navigation, you can access to the Dashboards page. Dashboards are fully customizable. Simply click on the Edit button (Image 3), and drag and drop on the desire widget. Additional widgets are available from VS Marketplace.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8935\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8935\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8935\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-3-Dashboards.png\" alt=\"Image 3 - Dashboards\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-3-Dashboards.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-3-Dashboards-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-3-Dashboards-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-3-Dashboards-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8935\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 3 &#8211; Dashboards<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>The widgets are interactive, for example you can use the new work item widget in order to create new item, or click the board link on the Work widget to jump to your Kanban board.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069572\"><\/a>Kanban boards and backlogs<\/h2>\n<p>The Kanban board is a feature of Azure boards, which allows you to plan your project using backlogs and boards (image 4). You can plan and track your entire release. From the Kanban boards, you can review your tests and tasks for each item.<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8936\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8936\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8936\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-4-Kanban-board.png\" alt=\"Image 4 - Kanban board\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-4-Kanban-board.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-4-Kanban-board-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-4-Kanban-board-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-4-Kanban-board-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8936\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 4 &#8211; Kanban board<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Using the backlogs (image 5), you can plan your Sprints by dragging and dropping an item to the desired sprint. Once in a sprint, you can use the Task board to track the progress. As engineers start a task, the can easily create branches for their work right from the board.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8937\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8937\" style=\"width: 1366px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8937\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-5-Backlogs.png\" alt=\"Image 5 - Backlogs\" width=\"1366\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-5-Backlogs.png 1366w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-5-Backlogs-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-5-Backlogs-768x432.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-5-Backlogs-1024x576.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1366px) 100vw, 1366px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8937\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 5 &#8211; Backlogs<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"green\"><span class=\"ion-info\">Tip (<a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/05\/31\/mastering-git-from-beginner-to-advanced-step-by-step-with-graphical-animation-commands\/\"><strong>Mastering Git with animation<\/strong>) <\/a><\/span> For more information about how to work with <strong>Git<\/strong> with animation. All commands will be represented in graphical animation. E.g. git branch, git merge, git rebase, git cherry-pick and many others, see <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/05\/31\/mastering-git-from-beginner-to-advanced-step-by-step-with-graphical-animation-commands\/\"> Mastering Git with animation <\/a><\/strong><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069573\"><\/a>Azure repos, Files, Commits, Pushes and Tags<\/h2>\n<p>This bring us to Azure repos, which supports both centralized version control, TFVC and distributed version control with Git. From Files, you can navigate to your repos content and even make quick edits (Image 6).<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8938\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8938\" style=\"width: 1366px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8938\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-6-Files.png\" alt=\"Image 6 - Files\" width=\"1366\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-6-Files.png 1366w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-6-Files-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-6-Files-768x432.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-6-Files-1024x576.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1366px) 100vw, 1366px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8938\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 6 &#8211; Files<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Commits allows you to see how your all branches come together. Pushes gives you a historic view of the changes pushed to the remote repository, while branches allow you to review all the branches and see if they are ahead or behind master. The Tags page not only allows you to review your tags, but even create new ones. Using the pull request page you can review and participate in pull requests. As your repositories allows you to leave rich comments during your pull requests and even apply policies that require a build to be executed.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069574\"><\/a>Azure pipelines<\/h2>\n<p>Azure pipelines is a rich cross-platform for CI\/CD system, capable of building any language targeting any platform (image 7).<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8939\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8939\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8939\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-7-Azure-Pipelines.png\" alt=\"Image 7 - Azure Pipelines\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-7-Azure-Pipelines.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-7-Azure-Pipelines-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-7-Azure-Pipelines-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-7-Azure-Pipelines-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8939\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 7 &#8211; Azure Pipelines<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>On the summary of a build, you can review the commit test results and much more. The deployment section allows you to see where in the release this build is currently. Editing a build definition is where you start seeing the real power. Azure pipelines can pull your code from the most popular source control systems (image 8).<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8940\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8940\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8940\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-8-Edit-a-build-definition.png\" alt=\"Image 8 - Edit a build definition\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-8-Edit-a-build-definition.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-8-Edit-a-build-definition-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-8-Edit-a-build-definition-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-8-Edit-a-build-definition-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8940\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 8 &#8211; Edit a build definition<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Azure pipelines also offers hosted Mac OS, Linux and Windows build agents. Adding tasks to your build is as easy as dragging and dropping from the collection of hundreds of open source tasks. In case you do not see the task that you need, simply search the marketplace, or write your own. Once the build is complete, Azure pipelines can deploy to any platform with releases. Releases, like builds provides hosted agents on Mac OS, Linux and Windows, and with the integration with App Center, can deploy to mobile as well (image 9).<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8941\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8941\" style=\"width: 1372px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8941\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-9-Releases.png\" alt=\"Image 9 - Releases\" width=\"1372\" height=\"774\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-9-Releases.png 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-9-Releases-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-9-Releases-768x433.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-9-Releases-1024x578.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1372px) 100vw, 1372px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8941\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 9 &#8211; Releases<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>You can also edit a release by clicking on the Edit pipeline button. You can pull the artifact to be deployed from almost everywhere, including other CI systems link Jenkins. Releases let you define environments and even assign approvers between them. From releases you have access to the same rich library of tasks and agents.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069575\"><\/a>Azure test plans and Artifacts<\/h2>\n<p>Azure test plans allows you to manage your entire testing effort across all your platforms and configurations. Here you can put all your planned and exploratory testing solutions. Azure artifacts allows you to apply the same DevOps best practices to the packages that you develop and maintain (image 10).<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8942\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8942\" style=\"width: 1366px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-8942\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-10-Azure-Artifacts.png\" alt=\"Image 10 - Azure Artifacts\" width=\"1366\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-10-Azure-Artifacts.png 1366w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-10-Azure-Artifacts-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-10-Azure-Artifacts-768x432.png 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/02\/Image-10-Azure-Artifacts-1024x576.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1366px) 100vw, 1366px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-8942\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image 10 &#8211; Azure Artifacts<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc500069576\"><\/a>Conclusion<\/h2>\n<p>This was just a quick glimpse of what is available from Azure DevOps for any language, targeting any platform. Each Azure DevOps service is open and extensible. They work great for any type of application regardless of the framework, platform, or cloud. You can use them together for a full DevOps solution or with other services. Get started today and see how Azure DevOps can accelerate your DevOps transformation.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Introduction How to access to your organizations and projects Kanban &hellip;<\/p>\n<p class=\"read-more\"> <a class=\"ast-button\" href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2019\/02\/04\/introduction-to-azure-devops\/\"> <span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Introduction to Azure DevOps<\/span> Read More<\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":9203,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"site-sidebar-layout":"default","site-content-layout":"default","ast-global-header-display":"","ast-banner-title-visibility":"","ast-main-header-display":"","ast-hfb-above-header-display":"","ast-hfb-bel